{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778596660306,"sessionID":"ses_1e3616403ffeC5P12i1rHrP0HR","part":{"id":"prt_e1c9f444f001dAI1jiswn58IhU","messageID":"msg_e1c9e9cc300167OEVV2RCjrUcm","sessionID":"ses_1e3616403ffeC5P12i1rHrP0HR","snapshot":"a05b74f3b39ce31f81977415201c1daa0ef94a34","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778596674911,"sessionID":"ses_1e3616403ffeC5P12i1rHrP0HR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"chatcmpl-tool-9b7a187a33bb5745","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/__issue_context__.json"},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/__issue_context__.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"body\": \"'[late embryo](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000323)' does not carry any sign that it should be reserved to some taxa (no explicit taxon restriction, and nothing in the definition that suggests it is not applicable to all metazoans).\\n\\nHowever, it is defined through '[late embryonic stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0007220)', which is itself '[preceded by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000062)' some '[pharyngula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004707)'.\\n\\nThe term “pharyngula” seems specific to vertebrates (or, at the very least, chordates). See for example:\\n\\n* [Masak & Davidson (2023)](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cdev.2023.203866): “Pharyngula: the stage in early vertebrate development when embryos share phenotypic characteristics”\\n* [Collazo (2000)](https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150050207357): “the pharyngula (the phylotypic and zootypic stage of craniates)”\\n* Ballard (1964): “pharyngula: a postneural stage characterized by the presence of pharyngeal clefts or grooves.” (Pharyngeal arches are themselves specific to chordates, so if they characterise the pharyngula stage, then it follows that the pharyngula stage is chordate-specific).\\n\\nFurthermore, the '[pharyngula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004707)' is '[preceded by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000062)' some '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)'.\\n\\nThough '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)' in Uberon is again not explicitly taxon-restricted, as far as I know, “neurula“ and “neurulation” are only ever used to refer to chordates. In GO, “neurulation” is an exact synonym for '[neural tube formation](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0001841)'; the concept of “neural tube“ is specific to chordates. In fact, Uberon’s '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)' is '[simultaneous with](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002082)' some '[neural tube formation](ht... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n3:   \"comments\": [],\n4:   \"title\": \"'late embryo' connected to effectively vertebrate-specific stages\",\n5:   \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3478\"\n6: }\n\n(End of file - total 6 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"body\": \"'[late embryo](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000323)' does not carry any sign that it should be reserved to some taxa (no explicit taxon restriction, and nothing in the definition that suggests it is not applicable to all metazoans).\\n\\nHowever, it is defined through '[late embryonic stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0007220)', which is itself '[preceded by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000062)' some '[pharyngula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004707)'.\\n\\nThe term “pharyngula” seems specific to vertebrates (or, at the very least, chordates). See for example:\\n\\n* [Masak & Davidson (2023)](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cdev.2023.203866): “Pharyngula: the stage in early vertebrate development when embryos share phenotypic characteristics”\\n* [Collazo (2000)](https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150050207357): “the pharyngula (the phylotypic and zootypic stage of craniates)”\\n* Ballard (1964): “pharyngula: a postneural stage characterized by the presence of pharyngeal clefts or grooves.” (Pharyngeal arches are themselves specific to chordates, so if they characterise the pharyngula stage, then it follows that the pharyngula stage is chordate-specific).\\n\\nFurthermore, the '[pharyngula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0004707)' is '[preceded by](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000062)' some '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)'.\\n\\nThough '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)' in Uberon is again not explicitly taxon-restricted, as far as I know, “neurula“ and “neurulation” are only ever used to refer to chordates. In GO, “neurulation” is an exact synonym for '[neural tube formation](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0001841)'; the concept of “neural tube“ is specific to chordates. In fact, Uberon’s '[neurula stage](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0000110)' is '[simultaneous with](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002082)' some '[neural tube formation](ht... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n  \"comments\": [],\n  \"title\": \"'late embryo' connected to effectively vertebrate-specific stages\",\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3478\"\n}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"__issue_context__.json","time":{"start":1778596674899,"end":1778596674909}},"id":"prt_e1c9f7372001yKbBabzB0IP7UG","sessionID":"ses_1e3616403ffeC5P12i1rHrP0HR","messageID":"msg_e1c9e9cc300167OEVV2RCjrUcm"}}
